content: Can't believe I never got around to rating this game. Had it for 2 years now, and still play it! Which oughta tell you something. Space trading, space battles, interstellar wars, and tons of ships and upgrades in an open ended story line that gives an excellent replay value. Battles are intense with multiple tactical options, depending on how you want to arm your ship. Gain wealth as a trader, become a pirate, explore the galaxy, or join the war effort, it's up to you. Lots of fun!

I want to give this game such high marks. It's right up there with escape velocity. There's a few little (but annoying quirks). You take a "defend from pirates" mission. Head to the system kill the pirates. Then if you don't head back to the place you accepted the mission you'll get a you failed message. Or you accept a "rush shipment" mission, to a system with two planets or a planet and a station... there's nothing to indicate which is which and if you guess wrong you get a failed mission.

Easily one of the best space 4x titles on the market. A perfect blend of trade, exploration, and combat (though the controls could be more responsive and precise. Perhaps a strafing function) sRPG3 doesn't let down for people who are fans of the "do literally whatever you want" motive that games like X3 Terran Conflict provide. It becomes easy to feel lost with so much and so little direction. but this is a game where you make your own fun, and there is plenty to be had in this sandbox. 10/10

content: This game might be a bit much for some people that are new to space sims. The ships are really small and hard to see even on a 5.6" screen, but it does give you a good idea of scale when seeing the battleships. The story was interesting, and even just being a space trucker reminded me of playing games like Elite: Dangerous. Late game got to be near dam impossible because the damage that the alien ships can do at a range you can't even calculate. I really enjoyed the time I had with this game and will be willing to buy the 4th iteration when it comes out. P.S. I had a weird bug that disabled my touch screen then I got a call or switched apps, so I had to reset the game every time.

On the whole I think this is an excellent game. You have captured much of a 
game I used to play called Escape Velocity. For years I have been searching 
for that games equivalent and have definitely stumbled upon it with this 
one. I love the open-world and storyline. What I am not wild about though 
are the controls. In combat I find them clumsy and landing and docking to 
be needlessly frustrating. Perhaps eliminating the speed factor in landing 
would help. The firing arcs are a little weird but I suppose add realism. I 
will end this on a positive note by simply saying that I'm very impressed 
with the AI. The fact that the enemy ships hide in your blind spot and make 
for difficult targets is very impressive given the fact that this game is a 
phone app. All in all well done I too await a sequel.

Could you please add an option to control the ship by tapping around the ship?  Basically move the joystick on top of the ship itself.  This is much more intuitive since you can see where you are pressing, see how the ship is responding and the feedback gives you much much greater control.   Games like starlost and others have this control system and there is a big difference. The game itself is great and has a lot of depth.  The oddball firing arcs of weapons is kind of irritating, but a better control system (and maybe an autofire toggle for non-torpedos) would likely alleviate a lot of this.  The targeting system feels weird too.  There should be a targeting indicator on the edge of the screen for off-screen targets so you can track easier.  Especially when you change targets as its difficult to see what you have targeted.  Ive mostly traded and avoided combat due to how klunky it feels.

Flying through space feels terrible in this game, you have a single thruster and your only options are forward thrust, reverse thrust, or turning awkwardly and trying again. The UI is clunky and there is next to no customization of the UI available. Music is only available in the main menu, once in game you are left with awkward silence. Not even your thrusters make noise, the only noise in this game is from weapons, and that is just random beeping. Although you are told you don't have to do the main storyline and you can choose what you want to do in this game, this is a lie. After doing a few random missions (deliver x to system y) you are railroaded into the main mission without a choice. Your cargo bay is filled and you have no choice but to complete the mission, followed by another main mission you are forced to complete. The final straw was when I tried to reload my game and accidentally pressed "New Game" instead of "Continue" as the buttons are fairly small and touch each other. A small text box appeared and informed me that starting a new game would erase my current save, but the ONLY option for you to press at this point is "okay", which promptly started a new game and wiped my save. This was my mistake, but I was dumbfounded that there was no cancel button on that pop up to allow me to back out. I tried to give this game a chance, it had great reviews and I love space games, but my advice is to save your money and not waste your time with this poorly made game.
replyContent: Hi Jacob I am sorry to hear you didn't enjoy the game. It may not be obvious but on the new game warning, there is an in-game arrow to go back in the top left that you can press, or you can press the physical or soft back button on your phone. The main missions initially capture you like that to introduce the story, but do ease-off after a few.

Wow. This game took me by surprise. It took me a little while to really get into it. But, once I did, I couldn't stop. It's downright brilliant. The game provides 12+ hrs of entertainment with loads of replay value. It's extremely well-thought-out and written. It includes actual role-playing; you make decisions as another individual, with appropriate rewards and consequences, not just hack-and-slash like what modern "RPGs" have become. But it has plenty of combat, all of which ramp with skill level and is almost always moderately difficult no matter what type of ship or armaments you be packing. Lastly, this seems like a dev who is really passionate about providing a better gaming experience. There are lots of details that lesser artists wouldn't even bother with; he has included all of them so the experience wouldn't be lacking. Pick this one up! I'm certainly happy I did!

Overall a really great game but there are some big issues! 1. Allied aggression: the other Allied ships can basically shoot each other and you all day without any penalty whatsoever whilst if you make one mistake like a stray bullet or missile then you basically get hunted down by your own team! I recommend making it to wear if you shooting your ally multiple times and then he and only he will shoot back a few times and return as a warning shot rather than hunt you down, and if you continue then you get hunted down by everyone. 2. Manual Navigation: even after I had unlocked the portal ring I never used it because it was so difficult to maneuver my ship close enough and slow enough to get it to work! I recommend you use your auto navigation and set up a menu where it says things like  [Navigate to FTL zone] [Navigate to Warp Ring] [Navigate to nearest landing pad] Things like that so you don't have to play Ring Around the Rosie with a moon. 3. Ally missles: I don't think I can even count the number of times of day to Allied missiles... as a solution I recommend that allies cannot damage you in anyway unless you damage them multiple times (see #1) 4. Protect missions: now I don't know if I'm just being stupid or not with this one but I can't seem to figure out how to do protect missions. I go to said area, I shoot the Baddies, and then 5 minutes later it tells me I failed.... I recommend like a wave counter (aka: how many waves of ships you have to defeat left) or a kill counter ( same thing as last one except with kills instead of waves)  Overall this Is a really great game and I'd be more than willing to give it a higher score if one or two of these issues were fixed (cough cough allies cough cough)

content: This game could be amazing. It's worth the price of admission as is, but it could be much better. The controls are a bit of a pain (the joystick stops following your finger if you move your finger too far, the targeting button doesn't always work/cycles through every target except the one you want) and the UI is very clunky. I haven't quite finished the main storyline yet, as I've been grinding to get a larger ship, but what I have played has been engaging. There is quite a bit of grinding involved, which some people may not like. There are many planets, but also many empty solar systems, which seems weird. Also there is usually only 1 planet per system, where's Mars, Venus? Did you love Escape Velocity Nova? Or even Star Control? Do you love space games where you pilot your vessel and upgrade or trade or pirate? You'll love this game.  here's a feeling of ownership in this game, that you're in control. Its clearly a labor of love by an independent dev. There are some bugs in the late stage inside the station but at least your game is saved every time you land. It's great to have such a game on mobile and it has the right balance of complexity and progression. Would love it if the author made a Space RPG Hardcore version with more items to trade and more ships yet keeping with the same progression.  I can't believe we're at SpaceRPG3 already, had I known about 1 and 2 I would have purchased them immediately.

I don't normally write reviews, but this is exactly the game I've been looking for. I loved EV Nova, and I've been on the lookout for a game like it to play on my phone. This has everything I could want, and the controls work great.
Great game , lots to think about

I dont write many reviews but this game more then deserves it. In this game you can do whatever you wish. From finding the most lucrative trade deals, pirating the defensless traders, and building your ultimate fleet.   The storyline lets you get a grasp as to what is going on in the universe and you can chose who and what you fight for.   For those that want to jump straight to base building or have finished the storyline you can build your own space station. Where you have to gather the materials to build and upgrade it. Once your base is complete you can engage in galactic warfare! Take your fleet into combat and conquor other systems to have axcess to there technology and ship to use it against them!   Space rpg3 is a game that is well worth taking a third look at if you are unsure. Just know that there is more then enough gameplay to keep you intertained and enough customization to do what you please
Awesome game. Great writing.
